id>2EE2B211-5088-4E18-9572-C8E47C26750E</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Christopher</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Montgomery</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FG005451%2F1"><gtr:id>9BA91E40-701C-4679-B0C4-FAB0CDC37A02</gtr:id><gtr:title>Perception of border dialects</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G005451/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This project will explore non-linguists? perceptions of language, with special attention paid to the Scottish-English border.&amp;nbsp; Border areas have been shown to be important areas of study, and it is in such areas that perceptual study could have many benefits in investigating whether phenomena important for linguists are also important for non-linguists.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />Previous studies that have gathered perceptual data from non-linguists have encountered problems in data processing.&amp;nbsp; Therefore, a major aim of the project is to address these problems by establishing firm links with relevant researchers working in other fields in order to perform a survey of resources that may be available (or could be adapted or created) in order to process perceptual data gathered from non-linguists.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; A small amount of pilot study research will be undertaken in order to investigate perception along the border, and provide information for use in the development of effective data processing tools.
&lt;br />
